The Telegraph - Calcutta
 Tuesday, November 26, 2002  Good Morning Hello It's Tuesday, November 26, 2002				 																Roads to avoid				 																																	 Southern Avenue: Work is in progress on a drainage pumping station.				 																																	 Chowringhee Road: A flyover is coming up.				 																Art on view				 																																	 Inauguration of an exhibition, Brahma to Bapu: Icons amp; Symbols in Indian Art, at CIMA Gallery, at 6 pm.				 																																	 The department of English and the Fine Arts Society of St Xaviers present Red and Black 2002, an arts and craft exhibition, at the college. Wasim Kapoor, Niranjan Pradhan and Tanu-shree Shankar will attend 				 																																	 Solo painting exhibition by Neelkant Choudhury, a Madhubani artist from Bihar, at The Address at 5 pm. Bangladeshi artist Shahabuddin Ahmed will inaugurate the show.				 																																	 An exhibition by eight artists at Chitrakoot Art Gallery, 3 pm to 8 pm.				 																Forum				 																																	 A literary forum meeting at Sahitya Akademi auditorium. Oriya writer Manoj Das will speak on Human predicament and the mystic folklore. Author Debesh Ray will chair the meeting.				 																Workshop				 																																	 The second session of Link the Arts, as part of the 10th anniversary celebrations of Sapphire Creations Dance Workshop, at Caffeine, Gol Park, 6 pm onwards. The evening will comprise a site-specific presentation using the natural wall as theme, a discussion on the need for alternative spaces for performance and a music jam session featuring Black Coffee.				 																Dance				 																																	 Priti Patel presents a dance recital at St James School, 12 noon, as part of Virasat 2002.
